in the Ruins of Capitalist Realism -- tConclusion: Thinking about ‘the Human’ during COVID-19 Times -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCutting across disciplines from science and technology studies to the arts and humanities, this thought-provoking collection engages with key issues of social exclusion, inequality, power and knowledge in the context of COVID-19. The authors use the crisis as a lens to explore the contours of contemporary societies and lay bare the ways in which orthodox conceptions of the human condition can benefit a privileged few. Highlighting the lived experiences of marginalized groups from around the world, this is a boundary-spanning critical intervention to ongoing debates about the pandemic. It presents new ways of thinking in public policy, culture and the economy, and points the way forward to a more equitable and inclusive human future. Chapter 12 is available Open Access via OAPEN under CC-BY-NC-ND licence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disease & Health Issues.2bisacsh1 aAiello, Giorgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmanatidou, Effie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, C.W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArthur, Keren Naa Abeka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBallo, Rokia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirabi, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuevas-Garcia, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Katy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodley, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https